snippet.textDisplay: The song's not as bad as it is being made out to be. In fact, the drums and guitar towards the end are amazing. But the problem with reconstructing a classic is that people will be, understandably, extra harsh on any shortcoming. In this case, it was RFAK being totally out of place in comparison to Ali Azmat. So, though it nowhere matches the excellence of the original, it is a pretty nice track in its own way.

snippet.textDisplay:
I don't think this was a bad attempt at all. In fact, I absolutely 😍 this rendition. True, that this was Ali Azmat's song, but this version is super cool too. I love both versions and I love going back and forth. Both give different flavours and I prefer not to compare rendition with the original. To me, Rahat Ali did what he is known for doing best... and most importantly, Ali Noor provided a great support to this version. His voice was not loud, but meaningful. No one can top Ali Azmat's version, that's for sure. But we all need to stop comparing versions and enjoy both versions in their own realms. It was a great mashup of song with instruments. Infact, every single musician contributed well and those high notes in the end ... Masha Allah!

Aur ager kisi ko phir bhi nahi acha laga, to Ali Azmat ka version to pehlay se hi para hua hai. Wo kabhi bhi sunn sakte ho, but then... what's the point of creating the same thing again?
